modernization of the nation.In Postal Culture, Gabriella Romani examines the role of the letter in Italian literature, cultural production, communication, and politics. She argues that the reading and writing of letters, along with epistolary fiction, epistolary manuals, and correspondence published in newspapers, fostered a sense of community and national identity and thus became a force for social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommunication and technologyzItalyxHistoryy19th century. 0aLetter writingzItalyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPostal servicezItalyxHistoryy19th century. 0aWritten communicationzItalyxHistoryy19th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266723540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442667235423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442667235.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK